  "research_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\"><strong>On the Ancient Orators</strong> is a rhetorical treatise by Dionysius of Halicarnassus, a Greek historian and teacher active in Rome during the late first century BCE. Composed in Attic Greek, the work is structured as a collection of critical prefaces originally written for editions of classical Athenian speeches. It functions as a forceful polemic and stylistic manifesto advocating for the classical oratorical tradition of fifth- and fourth-century Athens, exemplified by figures such as Lysias, Isocrates, and Demosthenes. Dionysius contrasts this Attic style, which he praises for its clarity, purity, and propriety, with the contemporary &quot;Asianist&quot; style, which he condemns as overly theatrical, bombastic, and intellectually hollow. His detailed analyses of individual orators serve to illustrate core aesthetic principles, linking effective expression directly to sound moral and intellectual character. The treatise is a foundational document of the Atticist movement, seeking to educate the Greek-speaking elite in Rome on the proper imitation of classical models. It survives in full through medieval manuscripts as part of Dionysius&#x27;s larger corpus of rhetorical works, valued by modern scholars both as a participant text in ancient stylistic debates and as a practical guide to rhetorical education.</p>\n</div>",
  "rows": [
    {
      "kind": "title",
      "reference": "t",
      "text": "ΔΙΟΝΥΣΙΟΥ ΑΛΙΚΑΡΝΑΣΕΩΣ ΠΕΡΙ ΤΩΝ ΑΡΧΑΙΩΝ ΡΗΤΟΡΩΝ Πολλὴν χάριν ἦν εἰδέναι τῷ καθ’ ἡμᾶς χρόνῳ δίκαιον, ὦ κράτιστε Ἀμμαῖε, καὶ ἄλλων μέν τινων ἐπιτηδευμάτων ἕνεκα νῦν κάλλιον ἀσκουμένων ἢ πρότερον, οὐχ ἥκιστα δὲ τῆς περὶ τοὺς πολιτικοὺς λόγους ἐπιμελείας οὐ μικρὰν ἐπίδοσιν πεποιημένης ἐπὶ τὰ κρείττω.",
